Language: en

00:00:00.870 --> 00:00:03.500
JONATHAN BERI: This session
we're going to talk about the

00:00:03.500 --> 00:00:09.135
Hangouts API and how far the
Hangouts platform has come

00:00:09.135 --> 00:00:12.170
over the year.

00:00:12.170 --> 00:00:13.800
Allow me to introduce myself.

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:15.510
My name is Jonathan
Beri, and I'm a

00:00:15.510 --> 00:00:18.032
developer advocate on Google+.

00:00:18.032 --> 00:00:22.410
If you have questions about
Hangouts, Hangout apps, or any

00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:25.630
other of the Google+ platform
features, please add me to

00:00:25.630 --> 00:00:26.570
your circles.

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:30.530
That's the best way to ask
me questions and start a

00:00:30.530 --> 00:00:32.930
conversation.

00:00:32.930 --> 00:00:36.290
Today's agenda, we're going to
talk about several things,

00:00:36.290 --> 00:00:39.520
starting with what is
the Hangouts API.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.640
For those of you who've never
seen the Hangouts API, I'll

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:46.020
give you an overview of the
features, why should you as

00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:51.280
developers build Hangout apps on
top of the API; go through

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:54.170
a bit of history to show where
we've come and where we're

00:00:54.170 --> 00:01:00.760
going; talk about the API
itself, how you can use it;

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:02.710
and then finish off with
the future, where

00:01:02.710 --> 00:01:04.849
we're going as a platform.

00:01:04.849 --> 00:01:06.670
Just a quick poll, how
many people have

00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:07.920
never been in a Hangout?

00:01:12.510 --> 00:01:14.650
All right, so we have some
people who are making jokes in

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:17.200
the front, Alan.

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:21.060
How many people have used
a Hangout App before?

00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:22.010
The mustache, most of you.

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:23.070
Great.

00:01:23.070 --> 00:01:27.720
So what's the Hangouts API?

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:32.460
Well, this is the effects app
that we ship with Google+, and

00:01:32.460 --> 00:01:33.660
it's a Hangout app.

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:36.966
And fundamentally a Hangout app
is an application that you

00:01:36.966 --> 00:01:40.400
as a developer can build that is
integrated into the Hangout

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:41.700
experience.

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:43.790
It's something you
can control.

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:46.910
It's something that you can
create new experiences around.

00:01:46.910 --> 00:01:49.350
And we as Google integrate that
for users, and they can

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:51.780
quickly and easily add that
to their conversation.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:55.990
The pieces are very simple.

00:01:55.990 --> 00:01:58.010
There's two major parts.

00:01:58.010 --> 00:01:59.890
It's JavaScript and HTML.

00:01:59.890 --> 00:02:02.690
It's regular code that we build
for the web, that you

00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:05.960
can either have Google host
or you can host yourself.

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:08.734
And it's the APIs that we extend
on top of the Hangout

00:02:08.734 --> 00:02:12.000
app to allow you to more deeply
integrate with the

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.495
overall video experience.

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:21.860
At the lowest level, a Hangout
app is just an iFramed app

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:24.330
that we shove into a Hangout.

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:27.080
So this is a mantra we like to
use around the platform team,

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:28.800
anything you can do
it in an iFrame

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:30.070
you can do in a Hangout.

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:32.140
So that opens up the
possibilities of the types of

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:34.710
applications you can build.

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:36.870
Because it's an iFrame
you can also host

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:38.860
it on your own servers.

00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:41.710
So you can use whatever back-end
services you want,

00:02:41.710 --> 00:02:45.520
whether it be Node or Python,
App Engine, Go.

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:48.770
You can use any database
you'd like, MySQL,

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:51.100
NoSQL, your SQL, whatever.

00:02:51.100 --> 00:02:52.900
You can use the existing
technologies that you're

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:55.180
comfortable with to build
Hangout applications.

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:00.220
So why would you want to
build Hangout apps?

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:06.170
If you're building apps today
for the web, you can bring

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:10.950
those applications into a
multi-user video experience

00:03:10.950 --> 00:03:13.910
that's real-time with
high engagement.

00:03:13.910 --> 00:03:16.840
So if you have a standard
application that's really

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:20.270
useful, let's say in a
collaborative sense, that it's

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:22.910
valuable to have a shared
activity, bringing that to

00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:26.510
Hangout lets you build on top of
that platform and add video

00:03:26.510 --> 00:03:29.240
and real-timeness for free.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:32.130
And it's built on top of
Google+, so you have that

00:03:32.130 --> 00:03:35.100
social network that can connect
users in a seamless,

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:37.060
integrated way.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:39.540
There's also another type of app
that's really exciting for

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:44.640
you as developers, and that is
to enhance the conversation.

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:48.150
Typically video chat platforms
may allow you to customize

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:50.510
some things, but with Hangout
apps you can actually tailor

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:52.760
the experience for the
type of conversations

00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:53.810
users want to have.

00:03:53.810 --> 00:03:56.280
Here's a screenshot of an
application called Hangout

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:00.150
Toolbox that allows you to see
who's talking and control

00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:02.660
volumes of all the speakers
and configure how the

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:04.310
conversation can flow.

00:04:04.310 --> 00:04:07.090
And you can use this for
broadcast scenarios or just

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:11.350
one-on-one with your
colleagues.

00:04:11.350 --> 00:04:13.810
Let's talk a little bit about
history, especially for those

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:17.750
who may not have built
Hangout apps before.

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:21.750
Here's a timeline of the
Hangout apps journey.

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:26.510
It all started in late 2011
when Google+ launched.

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:30.620
We didn't have apps, but Google+
Hangouts shipped with

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:34.290
a built-in application, the
YouTube application, that

00:04:34.290 --> 00:04:37.910
allowed users to watch a video
together as if you're on the

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:41.276
couch, even if you're millions
of miles away.

00:04:41.276 --> 00:04:43.980
You're not millions--
maybe thousands.

00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:46.980
But it sparked something
at Google.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:48.720
This is the type of experiences
that we want

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:49.970
developers to build.

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:55.180
So we started working on
the Hangouts platform.

00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:58.950
And we launched and developed
our preview in early 2012.

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:01.800
And from here on out we started
adding new features to

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:05.770
unlock new types of
applications.

00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:09.590
The first applications that we
built was the Effects app.

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:11.260
And it was neat.

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:12.480
It's fun.

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:18.320
It allows you to integrate
little animations, overlays,

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:20.590
within the video stream.

00:05:20.590 --> 00:05:23.840
It's very simple, fits on the
side of the screen, but it

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:26.010
sparked conversation.

00:05:26.010 --> 00:05:29.150
Wearing a mustache or a snorkel,
as silly as it

00:05:29.150 --> 00:05:33.560
sounds, can just start a whole
new thread of ideas.

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:36.290
And people at work are
using this to maybe

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:38.650
offload a little bit.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:40.720
And we saw these types of
applications being built from

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:43.320
the early days.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:46.530
A few months later we went
to general availability.

00:05:46.530 --> 00:05:48.500
That means developers could
actually ship their

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:53.370
applications to all
Google+ users.

00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:56.790
One of the first launched
apps was Scoot &amp; Doodle.

00:05:56.790 --> 00:05:59.380
It was built fully on the
application platform, and it

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:02.530
allowed people to
draw together.

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:04.240
You think about how simple
that is to do

00:06:04.240 --> 00:06:05.820
in your daily lives.

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:08.810
You're at your table with your
niece or your daughter and you

00:06:08.810 --> 00:06:10.210
want to draw together.

00:06:10.210 --> 00:06:11.950
That's great, but what
if you're traveling?

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:14.920
Scoot &amp; Doodle allowed you to
connect, even if you're in a

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:17.410
hotel room in Tokyo while your
kid's about to go sleep, and

00:06:17.410 --> 00:06:19.020
draw something together.

00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:22.390
And this app uses different
features of the platform, like

00:06:22.390 --> 00:06:24.980
those overlays we saw that
were a mustache.

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:28.390
They used this part to show
the crayon you're using.

00:06:28.390 --> 00:06:31.180
They also use the real-time APIs
that we built into the

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:35.830
platform to have the smooth
drawing experience seamlessly

00:06:35.830 --> 00:06:40.090
with that fun video piece.

00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:43.620
Then last year, I/O, I was on
a stage talking about how

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:46.780
Hangout apps have evolved,
and it was amazing.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:49.510
We had even more apps built on
the platform, more engaging

00:06:49.510 --> 00:06:53.450
types of conversations being
spunoff off these apps.

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:57.470
Here's another example that we
unlocked with another release.

00:06:57.470 --> 00:06:59.840
This is called "Donut Horns."
It was built by one of our

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:01.400
friends at an agency.

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:04.490
And at I/O we announced a facial
movement recognition

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:07.740
API, similar to the overlay,
that just sticks to your face

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:09.270
with a simple API.

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:14.130
This allowed you to build
interactive demos like this,

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:16.820
where you could become a unicorn
and catch falling

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:21.100
doughnuts, clearly something you
want to do at I/O. That's

00:07:21.100 --> 00:07:23.690
silly and fun, but this opens
up a whole new class of

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:27.940
applications, whether it be a
game like this or things for

00:07:27.940 --> 00:07:31.860
accessibility and helping you
communicate and control

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:35.900
real-time interactive media.

00:07:35.900 --> 00:07:39.280
And as we move forward we
released more and more APIs,

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:44.300
and the platform matured
and grew further.

00:07:44.300 --> 00:07:47.770
For example, we launched a app
called Cameraman to enhance

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:50.870
the broadcast controls to enable
Hangouts on the air to

00:07:50.870 --> 00:07:54.160
have a controllable experience
for those producers.

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:57.750
And then we exposed the API to
allow you to control who is in

00:07:57.750 --> 00:07:59.750
or not in the Hangout.

00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:03.060
We also had regular releases
improving the user experience

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:05.630
of Hangouts themselves to bring
Hangout apps to the

00:08:05.630 --> 00:08:09.080
forefront of the conversation.

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:12.150
And we're still shipping today,
still improving on the

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:15.360
platform and making progress,
adding new features, and

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:17.215
unlocking new potential
in the applications.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:23.970
So let's talk a little bit about
the actual API, a code

00:08:23.970 --> 00:08:27.110
you can write, a way
you can integrate.

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:32.419
The API is built on five
very simple principles.

00:08:32.419 --> 00:08:35.140
And these are methods that you
can invoke, events that you

00:08:35.140 --> 00:08:38.950
can listen to and respond to, to
make your apps interactive

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:42.650
and seamlessly integrate with
the video experience.

00:08:42.650 --> 00:08:45.380
These are just quick names,
but around people, the

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:48.470
real-time APIs, the video
effects themselves, and more

00:08:48.470 --> 00:08:51.420
information about the Hangouts
to tailor the UI.

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:52.670
Let's walk through
a few examples.

00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:58.220
Because this is a social
experience, a conversation,

00:08:58.220 --> 00:09:01.430
the most important API is the
one that's around people.

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:03.900
So I have a series of
participant APIs that allow

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:06.400
you to know who's in the
Hangout, who's just joined the

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.320
Hangout, who's leaving the
Hangout, so you can make your

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:11.940
applications respond to those
events and integrate their

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:15.010
social identity to make it
a personal experience.

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:17.800
Here's a screenshot of
Hangout Toolbox.

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:20.450
When somebody joins the Hangout
you can see who they

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:22.570
are and control their
speaking volume.

00:09:22.570 --> 00:09:24.870
If somebody has a booming voice
you can turn it down.

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:26.860
And if somebody's too soft
you can bump it up.

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:33.540
Another core class of APIs
is the real-timeness.

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:36.790
Hangouts themselves are
real-time and spontaneous.

00:09:36.790 --> 00:09:40.790
If Richard is in a Hangout
and I see him, I'll want

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:41.715
to join with him.

00:09:41.715 --> 00:09:43.310
It happens naturally.

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:46.480
So you have APIs around this
real-timeness of the Hangouts

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.180
themselves that you can
integrate into your

00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:49.350
application.

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:52.920
And we provide APIs as well that
allow you to add another

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:56.050
level of real-time
responsiveness.

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:59.910
Again with Scoot &amp; Doodle, they
use a series of APIs that

00:09:59.910 --> 00:10:02.800
we collectively call the
real-time APIs to draw the

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:05.430
points that the user
is drawing and then

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:08.260
smoothly show the path.

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:10.890
This is used for games,
like a "Donut Horn,"

00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:13.350
or a foosball game.

00:10:13.350 --> 00:10:15.780
And just like the Hangouts, you
can make your applications

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:17.380
responsive in real time.

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:25.265
And the last class of APIs is
around the video, manipulating

00:10:25.265 --> 00:10:28.720
the stream, adding the overlays
for fun and for

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:30.900
actual effectiveness.

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:34.140
Again, this is a combination of
a bunch of APIs, but they

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:39.010
overlay using the face-tracking
API.

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:40.450
The unicorn horn--

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:42.370
the unicorn game doesn't
actually have to write the

00:10:42.370 --> 00:10:45.150
code to figure out where your
face is and stick it on.

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:48.255
They just attach image to what
we call a face, and the

00:10:48.255 --> 00:10:49.930
Hangout tracks it for you.

00:10:49.930 --> 00:10:51.940
They have balloons in the
background that move up and

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:55.960
down, simulating a floating
balloon, using another API.

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:59.850
And then, of course, the facial
recognition API-- the

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:03.340
application can know where the
face is on the page and then

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:05.700
make the animation
respond to it.

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:10.220
These are just a few ways
to use the same APIs.

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:11.880
Now a little bit about
the future.

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:13.910
Richard Dunn here is to talk
more about where we're going.

