I'm Richard Dunn.

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:23.750
I'm the lead engineer for
the Hangouts API.

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:26.880
And Johnson just filled you in a
little bit of the history of

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:29.930
how the API got started
and the basics.

00:11:29.930 --> 00:11:32.400
And I get to do the fun
stuff, the demos.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.150
And those of you that have
been with us from the

00:11:34.150 --> 00:11:36.830
beginning will appreciate a lot
of the stuff that we've

00:11:36.830 --> 00:11:39.930
done here, just trying to work
out the kinks, make everything

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:41.180
work a little better.

00:11:43.710 --> 00:11:46.520
Where is the platform headed?

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:48.090
What do we want to
do in the future?

00:11:48.090 --> 00:11:50.940
And how do we want to make the
experience easier for you to

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:55.130
develop against and really try
to get a lot of good Hangout

00:11:55.130 --> 00:11:57.640
applications going?

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:00.190
Jonathan talked a lot about the
progress we've made over

00:12:00.190 --> 00:12:02.770
the last year and a half.

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:05.620
I feel like we've released
a lot of rich APIs.

00:12:05.620 --> 00:12:08.800
We've tried to cover all the new
features in Hangouts with

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:12.290
APIs so that you guys can build
the types of experiences

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:16.400
that we either haven't thought
of yet or haven't had the time

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:17.770
to work out.

00:12:17.770 --> 00:12:21.960
I think the volume control is a
really good example of that.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:24.990
You guys wanted to be able
to adjust that, and

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:27.480
you guys wrote it.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:29.440
So what do we want
to do from here?

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:33.090
The first thing we want to do is
really focus on faster and

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:35.510
more flexible releases.

00:12:35.510 --> 00:12:38.870
If you've followed along, we've
made regular updates to

00:12:38.870 --> 00:12:40.640
the platform.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:44.070
But I think that in a lot of
cases that was driven by us,

00:12:44.070 --> 00:12:47.290
and we want to fix it so that
it's driven by you more and

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:49.270
that we get stuff out as
soon as it's ready.

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:53.630
So we're always sitting there
coding new APIs, and we want

00:12:53.630 --> 00:12:54.590
to make sure that
they're in your

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:58.170
hands as fast as possible.

00:12:58.170 --> 00:13:00.680
And as I said, we really want
to get your feedback.

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:04.100
So we want to be building APIs
based on the kind of things

00:13:04.100 --> 00:13:06.336
you guys want to build
applications on.

00:13:06.336 --> 00:13:10.120
We want to hear from you about
what the APIs should look

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:12.080
like, to just make it easier
for you to write your

00:13:12.080 --> 00:13:13.810
applications.

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:16.800
And we want you to test stuff
out that we want to try out

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:19.280
and let us know how it works.

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:20.950
And of course, we're Google.

00:13:20.950 --> 00:13:22.410
We always want to release
cool stuff.

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:26.130
So we're going to
keep doing that.

00:13:26.130 --> 00:13:28.510
Let's talk about the first thing
we're going to do that

00:13:28.510 --> 00:13:33.190
enables us to release
things faster.

00:13:33.190 --> 00:13:36.640
So for those of you that have
been following along, we've

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:39.070
had a series of versions.

00:13:39.070 --> 00:13:41.400
And as of today we're actually
going to switch to a new model

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.390
for releasing API.

00:13:43.390 --> 00:13:46.310
Anyone that's familiar with
Chrome knows that Chrome uses

00:13:46.310 --> 00:13:50.350
sort of a channel model where
you can follow a stable and a

00:13:50.350 --> 00:13:52.740
beta channel and that
kind of thing.

00:13:52.740 --> 00:13:55.230
And within those channels
things are just pushed

00:13:55.230 --> 00:13:56.030
automatically.

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:58.680
So we're going to do that.

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:00.460
No more versions.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:05.970
Instead of batching up APIs
and releasing them in a

00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:10.550
particular version, we're just
going to have one channel, and

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:12.900
it'll go ahead and update
automatically with all the new

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:14.960
stuff we come out with.

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:16.900
So this is going to be
the stable channel.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:18.600
We're going to have
a stable channel.

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:20.420
If you've written an app before,
you know it's just

00:14:20.420 --> 00:14:22.640
basically a single JavaScript
include.

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:24.720
We've changed it a little bit.

00:14:24.720 --> 00:14:28.520
You'll notice there's no real
version number in here.

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:32.250
So when we release new stuff,
it'll just automatically come

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:33.540
into this channel.

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:35.950
The stable API is what you're
going to be using in all of

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:39.670
your public applications.

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:42.900
It's going to have the APIs
that we've very thoroughly

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:46.220
tested and run by and
made sure that

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:48.710
everyone is happy with.

00:14:48.710 --> 00:14:51.430
So this is the stuff that
we're very confident.

00:14:51.430 --> 00:14:56.510
So far we've essentially made
all stable releases, so just

00:14:56.510 --> 00:15:00.950
imagine that continuing but
on a faster schedule.

00:15:00.950 --> 00:15:03.060
The fun new stuff, though, is
we're actually introducing a

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:06.240
second channel, which is
a developer channel.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:08.640
And this is where we're going to
have basically use this as

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:11.460
a playground for new features.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:16.010
This is where we're going to
put stuff that we have

00:15:16.010 --> 00:15:18.350
developed internally but
maybe isn't quite

00:15:18.350 --> 00:15:20.270
ready for prime time.

00:15:20.270 --> 00:15:23.140
This is where we'll release new
APIs initially so that you

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:27.040
guys can give us feedback on do
they look right, do they do

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:30.230
all the things that you
want to do, is it too

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:33.400
complicated, et cetera.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:36.340
This will be for non-public
applications.

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:40.010
So if anyone's familiar with
developing, you can set your

00:15:40.010 --> 00:15:41.610
app to be public.

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:43.290
This for your private
applications.

00:15:43.290 --> 00:15:44.590
This is for you to
play around with.

00:15:47.420 --> 00:15:49.460
As I said, everything's not
ready for prime time.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:52.630
It's going to be a little bit of
the Wild West in there, but

00:15:52.630 --> 00:15:55.180
I think you guys will
have fun with it.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:59.760
But on that note, we want you
to actually be using these

00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:02.800
private applications and testing
them out and trying to

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:05.370
use them in real world.

00:16:05.370 --> 00:16:08.040
So also today we're going to
announce a new developer

00:16:08.040 --> 00:16:09.550
experience.

00:16:09.550 --> 00:16:13.020
Anyone that's developed a
Hangout app knows that we have

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:17.550
this isolated sandbox that
you run in right now.

00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:19.960
That's where you run your
developed apps.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:20.920
It's a little bit wonky.

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:23.440
You can't invite people,
it's not related to

00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:25.010
post, things like that.

00:16:25.010 --> 00:16:28.300
A lot of Hangout app developers
are also very

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:29.630
active in Hangouts.

00:16:29.630 --> 00:16:32.010
So there's this disconnect
between the apps they're

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:35.350
developing and the Hangouts
they're in.

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:37.130
So we're going to introduce
a new developer experience

00:16:37.130 --> 00:16:39.420
that's going to let you
run your private

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:41.310
apps in regular Hangouts.

00:16:41.310 --> 00:16:44.120
And I'm just going to go ahead
and demo that, so bear with me

00:16:44.120 --> 00:16:45.370
a little bit here.

00:16:48.110 --> 00:16:49.360
If I go into a Hangout--

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:56.460
and everyone's familiar with
the basic UX here.

00:16:56.460 --> 00:16:59.270
I've got some apps on
the left, et cetera.

00:16:59.270 --> 00:17:03.970
And if I go into our app
picker, you'll see the

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:05.770
featured and recent tabs.

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:08.319
And what we've added is
this developer tab.

00:17:08.319 --> 00:17:11.109
Anyone that's been in the
sandbox has seen this.

00:17:11.109 --> 00:17:14.460
And if I go into that, this'll
actually list the apps that

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:16.900
I'm currently developing.

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:21.650
So I just put in one of our
sample apps as a test here.

00:17:21.650 --> 00:17:24.810
And you can see that I can load
it, and I have, at the

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:28.510
top, the familiar
developer bar.

00:17:28.510 --> 00:17:31.410
This lets me do stuff
like reload the

00:17:31.410 --> 00:17:32.720
app, reset the state.

00:17:32.720 --> 00:17:34.930
This is great if you're just
sitting there hacking the

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:36.380
JavaScript.

00:17:36.380 --> 00:17:38.720
Really lets you figure it out.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:40.890
I'm just going to go ahead and
start another application real

00:17:40.890 --> 00:17:43.270
quick, for the sake
of the demo.

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:45.450
OK, so I'm just in a Hangout.

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:48.270
I've got a regular public
app, doesn't have

00:17:48.270 --> 00:17:49.720
any developer tools.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:53.720
I have an app that I'm working
on, has the developer tools.

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:56.180
And let's go ahead and
get somebody in this

00:17:56.180 --> 00:17:57.400
Hangout with me.

00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:00.180
I'm just going to Hangout
with myself, because

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:01.430
that's always fun.

00:18:03.810 --> 00:18:10.020
And when my other half comes
in, we can see that I'm

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:13.410
running the public app, the
effects app, but I don't see

00:18:13.410 --> 00:18:14.190
my developed app.

00:18:14.190 --> 00:18:18.580
So the developed apps are run
privately within the Hangout.

00:18:18.580 --> 00:18:20.510
So this is great if you're
just wanting

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:21.990
to test it out yourself.

00:18:21.990 --> 00:18:25.170
It's not really ready, but you
just want to play around with

00:18:25.170 --> 00:18:28.260
the app in a real-world
environment.

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:31.120
You get real people in there.

00:18:31.120 --> 00:18:33.050
But of course, that's no fun.

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:35.680
You want to test it with
real people as well.

00:18:35.680 --> 00:18:38.200
So what we've added is another
button to the developer

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.920
toolbar, which allows you
to share the app.

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:43.300
And what this is going to do
is basically give everyone

00:18:43.300 --> 00:18:46.830
else in the Hangout with you a
one-time pass to play around

00:18:46.830 --> 00:18:47.480
with this app.

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:50.290
So as long as they're still in
the Hangout with you, they can

00:18:50.290 --> 00:18:53.160
see the app, they can
interact with it.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:56.860
They move on to another Hangout,
they don't have it.

00:18:56.860 --> 00:18:59.260
So basically this is great
for beta testing.

00:18:59.260 --> 00:19:01.480
You can get your developers
in there.

00:19:01.480 --> 00:19:03.990
If anyone's done this before,
you have this weird thing

00:19:03.990 --> 00:19:05.650
where you had to add
people to the teams

00:19:05.650 --> 00:19:06.630
and things like that.

00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:07.640
We're just making it easier.

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:09.280
So let me just demonstrate.

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:12.950
You can see on the left, I can
still see only that I'm in the

00:19:12.950 --> 00:19:14.660
public effects app.

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:18.660
But if I as the developer hit
Share App here, now everyone

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:21.540
else in the Hangout
can see it.

00:19:21.540 --> 00:19:24.910
And they go in, and they can
run the app as normal.

00:19:24.910 --> 00:19:27.370
We are going to put up a little
warning, just to make

00:19:27.370 --> 00:19:31.990
sure that the other side knows
that this is a developed app,

00:19:31.990 --> 00:19:35.010
it's maybe not ready for
prime time, et cetera.

00:19:35.010 --> 00:19:41.370
But as soon as they click
through they can run it.

00:19:41.370 --> 00:19:43.250
Come on.

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:46.030
All right, well, let's not
worry too much about it.

00:19:46.030 --> 00:19:47.270
But let's assume that's
going to load.

00:19:47.270 --> 00:19:48.520
There we go.

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:54.500
The demo gods are not
smiling on me.

00:19:54.500 --> 00:19:56.880
You get the general
idea, though.

00:19:56.880 --> 00:20:00.230
They'll be able to see the app
just like everyone else.

00:20:00.230 --> 00:20:01.860
Let's go back to there.

00:20:01.860 --> 00:20:03.890
That's our new developer
experience.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:06.400
Just to sum up, no
more sandbox.

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:09.040
We're actually going to end
up retiring the sandbox.

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:11.160
We'll give you a little time
to get used to the new

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:14.130
experience, but basically just
going to retire it and move to

00:20:14.130 --> 00:20:15.100
this model.

00:20:15.100 --> 00:20:18.110
And you'll just, as you're
developing apps, develop them

00:20:18.110 --> 00:20:19.440
in regular Hangouts.

00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:21.690
Obviously you can just be in a
Hangout with yourself and play

00:20:21.690 --> 00:20:23.470
around with it in there, but
if you want to bring other

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:26.570
people into it, see how it works
in the real world, or

00:20:26.570 --> 00:20:32.160
even share it with them, you
can run it privately or you

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:34.120
can share with others
in your Hangout.

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:36.493
So that's our new developer
experience.

00:20:36.493 --> 00:20:40.750
[APPLAUSE]

00:20:40.750 --> 00:20:42.520
RICHARD DUNN: I can see some
of the veterans in the room

00:20:42.520 --> 00:20:45.780
are happy with that.

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:47.280
So we have this new
channel model.

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:48.570
We're giving you new stuff.

00:20:48.570 --> 00:20:50.800
And I wouldn't want to give you
new stuff without actually

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:53.530
giving you new stuff, so we
also have some new APIs to

00:20:53.530 --> 00:20:56.580
announce today in both the
stable channel and the

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:58.170
developer channel.

00:20:58.170 --> 00:21:00.780
So let's start with the
stable channel.

00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:03.800
Jonathan pointed out that one
class of apps that really

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:07.280
helps is these enhancement apps,
the things the tend to

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:10.870
run in the sidebar that set the
experience of the Hangout

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:12.360
the way you want it.

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:16.300
Things like effects, things like
volume control, things

00:21:16.300 --> 00:21:19.450
like, anyone that's watched an
HOA, the very popular Lower

00:21:19.450 --> 00:21:23.750
Thirds application that lets me
show a title, these are the

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:26.260
kinds of things that a lot of
people there are in a lot of

00:21:26.260 --> 00:21:28.420
Hangouts are just bringing
up every time

00:21:28.420 --> 00:21:29.580
they go into a Hangout.

00:21:29.580 --> 00:21:31.570
So why should you actually
have to click on

00:21:31.570 --> 00:21:33.110
that app to run it?

00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:35.200
Why don't we just
load it for you?

00:21:35.200 --> 00:21:39.350
We're introducing a new API
today to let the app autoload

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:42.380
itself whenever you
go into a Hangout.

00:21:42.380 --> 00:21:43.630
So let's demo that.

00:21:46.870 --> 00:21:48.120
I'm going to get out
of this Hangout.

00:21:50.840 --> 00:21:53.260
This is the Hangout Toolbox.

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:55.950
Anyone that's familiar with
this, it's basically a bunch

00:21:55.950 --> 00:21:58.000
of utility things.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:21:59.070
And one of the more--

00:21:59.070 --> 00:22:02.370
I'm going to go ahead
and close this--

00:22:02.370 --> 00:22:05.730
popular ones is the
Lower Third.

00:22:05.730 --> 00:22:14.195
So here, if you've watched the
news, I can set a lower third

00:22:14.195 --> 00:22:18.200
that gives my name, what
I do, et cetera.

00:22:18.200 --> 00:22:20.240
This is great if you're just
coming into a Hangout, maybe

00:22:20.240 --> 00:22:23.190
you're with strangers, you want
to give them a little bit

00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:26.210
of an update as to
who you are.

00:22:26.210 --> 00:22:28.370
And as I said, it's great on
an HOA where you don't

00:22:28.370 --> 00:22:33.100
necessarily have the context
of seeing who's in there.

00:22:33.100 --> 00:22:37.420
We've added a new option that
lets an application set itself

00:22:37.420 --> 00:22:39.380
to be auto-loaded.

00:22:39.380 --> 00:22:42.470
So they've updated their app
here to enable that.

00:22:42.470 --> 00:22:44.420
And I can actually
click this on.

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:47.900
And when I click this on, I'll
get a little warning that lets

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:49.880
me know that this is going to
auto-load the next time I

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:54.490
want, I can undo it, all
that kind of thing.

00:22:54.490 --> 00:23:07.830
But if I did really want this
and I go into another Hangout,

00:23:07.830 --> 00:23:10.040
it has already started.

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:11.800
And in fact, you can see
that my Lower Third

00:23:11.800 --> 00:23:13.190
popped up as well.

00:23:13.190 --> 00:23:15.200
I'm going to give a little shout
out to the Drive team,

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:18.620
who has a new API for
application data.

00:23:18.620 --> 00:23:20.860
And I think this is a great
way to basically let an

00:23:20.860 --> 00:23:24.310
application store, say,
a config file.

00:23:24.310 --> 00:23:28.400
And what they've done with
Toolbox is say, we'll store

00:23:28.400 --> 00:23:29.670
your Lower Thirds.

00:23:29.670 --> 00:23:31.950
And when you auto-start, we'll
actually auto-turn-on your

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:32.540
Lower Thirds.

00:23:32.540 --> 00:23:34.350
So anyone that's done a
lot of HOAs is going

00:23:34.350 --> 00:23:36.300
to love this feature.

00:23:36.300 --> 00:23:39.190
We really encourage anyone
that's doing an enhancement

00:23:39.190 --> 00:23:43.090
app that they think would be
useful to run in every Hangout

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:44.850
to turn this on.

00:23:44.850 --> 00:23:47.700
And we'd love to see a lot more
of these kind of tools

00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:50.100
that let you shape the
experience of a Hangout.

00:23:55.350 --> 00:23:58.930
To sum up, you can now set
your app to auto-load.

00:23:58.930 --> 00:24:03.150
The user will confirm that
this is what they want.

00:24:03.150 --> 00:24:05.400
You might want to look into
some of the Drive stuff.

00:24:05.400 --> 00:24:09.040
And I encourage you go to some
of the Drive talks to see how

00:24:09.040 --> 00:24:12.510
you might make that experience
as seamless as possible.

00:24:12.510 --> 00:24:14.940
You could even imagine hiding
the app when it comes up and

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:17.890
knows exactly what
it wants to do.

00:24:17.890 --> 00:24:20.470
And this is really allowing you
to set your Hangout the

00:24:20.470 --> 00:24:23.420
way you want it.

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:25.880
So that's going to be in
the stable channel.

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:28.790
So that'll actually be available
for public apps

00:24:28.790 --> 00:24:30.040
immediately.

00:24:32.200 --> 00:24:35.640
In the developer channel
we basically have

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:37.280
a set of new effects.

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:41.950
And I think that these effects
are fairly exciting.

00:24:41.950 --> 00:24:43.780
But they still need some
tweaking, so that's why we're

00:24:43.780 --> 00:24:47.640
putting them in the developer
channel and we're letting you

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:51.650
take a look at them, use them
out, and give us feedback on

00:24:51.650 --> 00:24:52.980
how they're working.

00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:54.680
Let me demonstrate
two of those.

00:24:57.590 --> 00:25:00.220
I'll leave this Hangout.

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:03.400
The first one, for those of you
that are familiar with our

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:08.950
facial tracking, should come
as an expected evolution of

00:25:08.950 --> 00:25:13.770
that, and that is
hand tracking.

00:25:13.770 --> 00:25:19.290
Oh, that's not good.

00:25:19.290 --> 00:25:22.720
Oh, actually, I know exactly
what's happening there.

00:25:25.700 --> 00:25:29.640
Does anyone want to sit here
and wait while I fix it?

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:32.900
I think we can fix it.

00:25:32.900 --> 00:25:34.760
Why don't I skip to the
other one while

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:36.010
I'm fixing it, though?

00:25:39.310 --> 00:25:40.460
Actually, I'll just
talk through it.

00:25:40.460 --> 00:25:44.450
Hand tracking, I think it's
fairly straightforward.

00:25:44.450 --> 00:25:46.640
We've had facial tracking
for quite a while.

00:25:46.640 --> 00:25:50.850
So you've had the ability to
see the face, see points on

00:25:50.850 --> 00:25:55.690
the face, track them along,
put the overlays on top.

00:25:55.690 --> 00:25:57.300
Jonathan mentioned
the Effects app.

00:25:57.300 --> 00:26:01.490
We've had the snorkel mask
and let that do it.

00:26:01.490 --> 00:26:03.580
But you can also actually
track the face.

00:26:03.580 --> 00:26:06.430
So if you want to write your
own game logic or whatever

00:26:06.430 --> 00:26:09.690
that deals with that, you can.

00:26:09.690 --> 00:26:11.120
And so we've added
this for hands.

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:13.920
So now if I hold my hand up, we
can actually identify the

00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:17.000
center of the hand and track the
hand as you're doing it.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:20.290
So you could imagine writing
applications where somebody

00:26:20.290 --> 00:26:23.270
raises their hand to answer a
question and the app actually

